# Navigating GBVIMS+

### Logging In​

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

To use GBVIMS+ the rollout will need to be endorsed by the GBVIMS Steering Committee. Once that happens and the criteria and resources required are met, then the system will be set up by a system administrator. That administrator will provide log-in information for users to access the system.To log in to Primero/GBVIMS+ you will need a username and password that should be assigned to you.  Click in the username box and type in your unique username.  Then, enter your password in the field below.

### Dashboard or Home Page​

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

Clicking on the Primero icon from any page will take you back to the dashboard. This is where you can quickly find information about the cases and incidents you have access to. This includes recently created or modified cases or incidents.

### Header Navigation Bar​

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

The header navigation is the dark bar across the top of the screen in which you can navigate to your home page \(or dashboard\), cases, incidents, and reports.  It also has a quick search field that can help you find a specific case quickly. ​Depending on your role \(casework, supervisor, coordinator, etc.\) your dashboard or header navigation bar will look a little different. The header navigation bar functions just like a menu bar on any website. Clicking on any part of the bar will direct to that page.

### Logout, My Account and Contact & Help Links​

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

Above the Header Navigation bar, there are small links that bring you to pages that allow you to logout of the system, help to manage your account and contact information, as well as find out who is your organization system admin.

### List View​

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

When you want to see a list of the cases or incidents you have access to, click on ‘cases’ or ‘incidents’ from the header navigation to see a list.  This shows you all the cases or incidents you have access to. This list can be filtered or sorted. You can also click on any ID to look at that case or incident individually.

### Filtering​

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

To the right of the list view you’ll see the filter function. You can filter the list view to narrow down to a case/ cases. For example, you can filter the list to show females only, but you can also filter by specific type of violence, and the incident report date range.

### Quick Search​

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

You’ll also notice above the filter panel a quick search function. From here you can type in your search and return a list of possible matches. This is useful when searching for a specific name or case ID. ​

### Action Buttons and Anchored Header​

The action buttons are located just below the header navigation bar. In what is called the **Anchored Header**, meaning it stays at the top of the screen when scrolling.This allows users to perform action on an individual case or multiple cases. ​

The possible _**actions**_, depending on your permission, include: ​

* Flag​
* Import ​
* Export​
* Refer​
* Transfer​
*  Assign

Please note, these actions are dependent on your role in the system. Some users don’t have the ability to transfer for example so that button would not appear for them.​

### Flags

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

Flags can be used in the incident and case sections to flag a case for follow up. You can include a reason and a date. Supervisors can also flag cases for caseworkers. Flagged cases will appear with a flag on the cases or incidents page. You can un-flag a case by clicking on the case and including a reason for unflagging the case. The system will automatically keep a record of flags for each cases or incident. You can also filter to flagged cases or incidents in the filter panel.
